What is bash?

Bash is a programming language that is used in a command line. There are many different types of programming languages. Bash is commonly used on Macs, Linuxs, and now even PCs. It is similar to C-shell languages like csh, tcsh, and Apples zsch.

Why use bash?

Generally, what can be done in one programming language, can be done in any programming language. But somethings are easier to do in particular languages. With Bash, its easy to do simple things, but very complicated to do complicated things. That may seem obvious, but in some languages like python, doing complicated things can sometimes just be one line of code. In this tutorial, we will go over some of the easier, basic functions of bash. Here are some examples of easy things that can be done in bash:

  • Move, copy, and delete files
    • This is replacing your mouse, with the advantage being that you can manipulate lots of files at the same time instead of pointing and clicking a thousand times.
  • Download programs and packages
    • Think Internet Explorer or Microsoft Edge. Its only useful for downloading Google Chrome.
    • Bash can be used to install packages (mini-programs) that are used by python and R.
  • Run programs and scripts
    • When you create scripts in other languages (like python and R), these scripts can be run using bash, instead of opening a python intepretor, opening your file manually, and running the code.

Using a text editor

As well learn throughout the week, there are a variety of different ways to write code. One way is to use an integrated development environment (IDE), such as this tutorial which was written in RStudio or Jupyter which was used to create the python tutorial. We will demonstrate how to use these later in the week. Another way to edit and write is to use a text editor. This can just be a notepad document. However, some more fancy software exists which makes it very helpful to write code by stylizing code so that it is easier to read, like the example below.

I would recommend Visual Code Studio. As you work through this tutorial, type your example code, solutions, and anything else you are entering in the terminal into the text editor as well. That way when you run a bit a code today, youll have a copy of it for future use. Probably the most useful part of coding is re-usability, which is where the text editor comes in. You can also add comments to code to make notes on what a certain command does. This can be done by adding a # at the beginning of a line. Everything on the line after the # will not be executable as code. Try using comments to describe the commands you use throughout the tutorial.

At the end of the tutorial we will also use a text editor to create a script. Scripts allow us to write out a series of commands or instructions that is then carried out by the program (today, in bash) and can be executed many times as opposed to being utilized in a single instance.

Basic Bash Commands

Terminal

The terminal is a way of interacting with your computer that does not require a graphic user interface (GUI). In the olden times, computers did not have a mouse, a desktop, folders, or program icons. If you wanted to do something on a computer, you had to give the computer very specific instructions (sometimes referred to as commands). If the terminal is the old way of doing things, why do people still use the terminal today?

One reason, and a point we will stress throughout the bootcamp, is for automation. When you interact with a computer as you regularly do with a GUI and a mouse, you will have to repeat very redundant motions. Lets say you want to rename 100 files. You will have to right click on each one, hit rename, and then type out the new name of the file, all while making small but infuriating mistakes at each of these steps. Repeating this process over and over, you might also make small mistakes that can be harder to catch later, like if you were to add an extra a in a name somewhere. With the terminal, and with coding in general, we can save ourselves a ton of time by creating a set of commands, testing them on a couple of files, and then running them on all of the other files using a script or our text file once we know that they work like we want them to. If later we want to do a similar thing for a new set of files, or even change the names of the files we already edited, were even closer to completing that goal than we were in the first place because we can just modify that original script.

Listing

When you open a folder using the GUI on your computer, you can immediately see the files that are inside. In the terminal you will have to give it a command to see what is inside (ignore this con, the pros are coming soon). The command to list the contents of the current directory is:

ls

But what is a current directory, or even a regular directory. You can think of a directory as a folder, and the current directory would be the current folder. Okay, so now we can see what is in our current directory, but where are we anyways?! Well, if we were using our computer the traditional way, we might have a bar at the top of our finder window that lists the entire address of where we are. In the terminal, we will also have to provide the command to Print the Current Directory.

pwd

Directories

Another word you might see used is subdirectory, which is just a directory within a directory. Directories are relative and so any given directory can be a subdirectory, depending on your point of reference. One import directory to know is the home directory. Computers have a default directory where you generally start once you open the terminal. If you ever find yourself somewhere and want to go to the home directory, just use the change directory command:

cd

Navigating Directories

Navigating through directories is like navigating through a city. There are streets that need to be followed in order to get to a specific house. In the real world, there are multiple ways to get to a single location like your house. But for this example, imagine there is only one set of directions to get to your house. That is what navigating your computer through a terminal is like (note: this is not true, but using short cuts in the terminal can be very tricky, so we are not going to talk about that). So imagine you are at Weiss Hall on Temple Universitys campus and you want to get to City Hall. What are the directions that you would need to take? Cecil B. Moore to Broad st. to City Hall. When you navigate through your computers directory structure, you cant just say the final location of the file you are looking for, you need to give it a path, like how we just described going from Weiss Hall to City Hall.

Know where you are going

To navigate through directories, we can use the cd command and input a subdirectory to go to there. For example, use the following command to go to the Desktop from the home directory:

cd Desktop

Now when we hit ls we can see everything on our desktop: ~

Here, we only needed one step to get to where we needed to go. For example, we are already on Broad St and the next stop is our destination, City Hall. But what about when you are a few steps away from your destination?

Going to where you need to go

Now that you know the ls, cd, and pwd commands, you can navigate through your computer just like you would with the finder (on a mac) or the file explorer (on a PC).

Managing Directories

Creating new directories

To create a new directory, use the make directory command while providing a name to the new directory:

mkdir test_directory

Here, we used an underscore to space out the words test and directory. This is because navigating through directories that have a space or other weird characters in the name can be tricky. So to keep things simple, coders often use underscores instead of spaces.

Creating subdirectories

We can also create subdirectories by giving a path and then the new subdirectory. The syntax for this is:

mkdir path/to/new/filename

Moving things

We can use the move command to move directories and other files. Here is the syntax for that:

mv path/to/file path/to/new/location

Renaming things

The move command can also be used to rename things. Normally, we would use the move command to move something to somewhere else by providing a path to the new location. To rename something, we wont provide a new path, but just the new name, like so:

mv old_filename new_filename

Copying things

The copy command can be used to copy files from one location to another location with the following syntax:

cp path/to/original path/to/new/location

Exercise 2.f

Copy over the subject data, in the logs, from the misc workshop directory into the subject_data subdirectory in the bash directory.

Note: In order to copy a directory and its entire contents, you must use the -r flag like so:

cp -r path/to/original path/to/new/location

Flags are different and additional options for a command. The -r flag here stands for recursive, so we are having the computer copy the directory and its entire contents as opposed to a single empty folder or a single file.

Hint: There are multiple ways to solve this exercise. First, you should note the correct paths. It might seem complicated, but just keep in mind that only two inputs are needed for this command. Removing things

Removing files can be done by providing the path the file you wish to remove. Again, if you wish to remove a directory, you used use the -r flag.

rm path/to/file

Note: Be very careful when you remove a file or directory using the terminal. If youve deleted files from your computer before, they generally end up in a separate Trash folder for a certain amount of time. THIS IS NOT THE CASE WHEN YOU REMOVE FILES USING THE TERMINAL. Files removed via the terminal are gone. Forever.

If-statements

Now that we know some basic commands, we can get to more complicated things. If-statements allow us to do something if certain a certain condition is met. The syntax for this is:

if logical_argument; then
  do something
fi

The logical arguments used here can be a variety of things. One thing you can use it for in data management is to see whether certain files exist. The following command will check to see whether a .csv file exists for a particular subject.

# The -e flag tells bash "We want to know if this file exists"
if (-e subject_data/subj_ID.csv); then

  # The echo command makes bash print the statement that follows it, but because it's placed in an If-statement, it'll only print it if the logical argument above it is true.
  echo "The data exists!"

fi

Elif

We can also add additional conditions. These kinds of situations involve something along the lines of if this do this, or if that do that, else do this. For example, maybe we forgot how we named our files. Lets try a couple of different file names, and if those dont work, well have it printed out that were failures.

if (-e subject_data/DE249/DE249_dbdm_run_01.csv); then
  echo "The first one was right!"
elif (-e subject_data/DE249/DE249_dbdm_run_1.csv); then
  echo "The second one was right!"
else
  echo "The file does not exist."
fi

The -e is a flag, which tells the command to do something specific. In this case -e asks does this exist.

For Loops

For loops allow us to repeat a set of commands. This is very useful when you want to do the same thing for a bunch of subjects. The syntax is:

for {thing} in {list_of_things}; do
  do this_to ${thing}
  and this_to ${thing}
  and that_to ${thing}
done

thing here becomes a variable. In order to reference a variable, you need to use the correct syntax, which is to have a $ in the beginning. It is also a good idea to have the whole variable name in curly brackets {}. If you did not use this syntax and just used thing instead, bash would think this is a folder called thing in the current directory.

Writing Scripts

Making an executable script

To run a script, we can save the file and then use bash to run all the commands in one command, rather than use copying and pasting each command into the terminal.   4. Change the permission to make the file executable by using the code below.

Symbolic links

Symbolic links are shortcuts for files in the terminal. These are useful for when you want to reference something in another directory, instead of creating a duplicate of that directory. For example, you have some data you are analyzing and want to try something new with it. You could copy the current directory and then just replace files with your new analysis. Or, you could create a master directory for your data, then create subdirectories for each analysis. Inside each analysis subdirectory, you could create a symbolic link to the original data.

The syntax to create a symbolic link is

ln -s /source/file /path/to/where/the/shortcut/goes

Reading files

Bash can be used to quickly see the contents of a text file. This can be done with cat.

cat [filename]

Note that its not only .txt files that can be read. Some text files have other extensions. For example, .csv files are actually text files with commas separating the cells. Try reading the HCP dataset .csv file using cat.

Filtering

As you can see, that was a lot of output and it was probably hard to make sense of any of it. Lets try filtering this data to find just a specific subjects data. We can do this by piping and then use grep to filter. Piping refers to running a command on the output of another command. The syntax to pipe is:

command1 ... | command2

The pipe character above is the character you get from hitting shift and backslash () on your keyboard.

Lets try filtering the output of the HCP data for a single subjects data

cat [filename] | grep [subjectID]

Saving outputs to files

We can save the output of commands to files by using the > or >> characters. > saves the output to a brand new file, and overwrites any file with the name you provide it. >> appends your output to a file of a given name. If such a file doesnt exist, it is created. Try playing around with both commands.

cat [filename] | grep [subjectID] > [output_file_name]

Searching for files/filepaths

Directory structures can be really confusing. Things can get lost, or sometimes you just want to get the path for something that you know exists somewhere in the current directory. For example, I know there are solutions to all the exercises in this tutorial and that all of the files have a .sh extension. Try to use the find command to find all the solution files. Heres the find syntax:

find . -name [part_of_file_name]
